title: Grateful Dead Live at Winterland Arena on 1972-01-02
description:
Set I
Truckin', Sugaree, Mr. Charlie, Beat It On Down The Line, Loser, Jack Straw, Chinatown Shuffle, Your Love At Home, Tennessee Jed, El Paso, You Win Again, Big Railroad Blues, Mexicali Blues, Playin' In The Band, Next Time You See Me, Brown Eyed Women, Casey Jones
Set II
Good Lovin'-> China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider-> Good Lovin', Ramble On Rose, Sugar Magnolia, Not Fade Away-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Not Fade Away, E: One More Saturday Night


Comment
Other artist(s): GD; NRPS; Yogi Phlegm

reviews.review_text:
Great Recording and Mastering Personally I don’t rate the performance or set of any Dead show, they are all great and you can research which shows to listen to as their “best”. 
On archive, I am strictly reviewing sound quality/upload of the recording this review is tied to. This newly mastered recording is excellent, clean, and has good highs and lows. Tracks are titled and in appropriate order

NY deuce
This was the only New Year's run that started on NYE – in fact shows were played on the 1st & 2nd (NYE started in the early morning hours of the 1st). This night was added after the Eve sold out. With the crazed bacchanalia that NYE became, it's interesting they would add a hangover show (albeit with one night to recover). It was the only time they would do this (sort of; they stayed up after NYE '66 and played in The Panhandle in '67). This was the last show before Bobby went to Wyo to write songs for Ace on Barlow's ranch. The next show is also at Winterland. This night has a huge, 16-song 1st set, and a one hour second set. It's known for having a Good Lovin' sandwich with a China Cat in the middle. First Set. It takes a few to warm up. After Sugaree, Bobby asks "Are we on the radio or can I speak my mind?", apparently about to berate the equipment or crew over tech issues? Phil/the rhythm section has been a little off, as on Mr. Charlie, but the uptempo Beat it on Down the Line-8½ sends the first smoke (they argue between 9 or 18 and it comes out 8½). It's the first great one of '72 (soon there will be 5/3, 5/7, etc.). Jer underplays the next two but the uptempo Jack Straw comes out unique. Chinatown is just the second one, and now in shape, becoming a show stopper in a few months. Some old setlists used to show "Your Love at Home" here. There is no song by that name and it was never played. It was a misinterpreted note, a prank, or an error. Or, there is a brief Bobby tuning that may have somehow reminded someone of the hymn Love at Home. The uptempo Tennessee Jed is otherwise the standard '72, but again there is not much Jer on El Paso. Pigpen is getting You Win Again ready for E72. Playing in the Band has an OOT start, remaining a bit rough. The first few secs of Next Time You See Me are missing, but it has the best ensemble playing of the set. Brown Eyed Women is again a standard '72 (notwithstanding the flubby end), but here she had twins eight times and also raised eight boys. So, doing the math: the twins, if identical, had to be girls, so that's 24 kids! Casey Jones accelerates to greater tempos, but the lack of fireworks in this set will be forgotten by the end of the second. Second Set. This Good Lovin' attracts attention because it has a Sunflower growing up in the middle. The 1st few secs are cut. After that it's a solid (if standard) GL, until 12mins when Phil starts a Hard to Handle jam. That winds down after 1min, then there's some reaching about until Phil starts another jam, that Jer again jumps upon in a nanosecond. After, Keith plays an arpeggio, then Jer actually starts playing Bobby's part (!) in China Cat, which Bobby immediately follows. But rather than a China Jam, Jer starts the verses. As they start to jam out of China, Jer stabs the return to GL like a dagger, and the others immediately fall back to the reprise. A must-hear-once sequence, with a rare (post-'69) China Cat w/out Rider. It's still mostly Bobby's show, giving the crucial axis on a standout Ramble On Rose, but Sugar Magnolia is just a little out of pocket. Not Fade Away is the set peak, and Billy is able to do things unobtainable with two drummers. Goin' Down the Road is extremely tight all around, but listen for Keith. Though this is a super tempo One More Saturday, Bobby is unruffled, implacable, delivering one of the most rocking versions. 1st Set:  C+ 2nd Set: B+ Overall = 3¾ stars Highlights: Beat it on Down the Line – uptempo & smoke Next Time You See Me – ensemble playing & Pigpen Ramble On Rose – the Bobby axis Not Fade Away>Goin' Down the Road Feeling Bad – Billy & Keith respective foci One More Saturday Night – super tempo, delivered SOURCES: The 161838_sbd restores the tunings and fixes the pitch errors. The sbd_eD_8709 runs slow.
